subSubSection.paragraph:
Male pedipalpus (

Figs 
2–4

): Tibia well developed and expanded, longer than wide, ventrodistal margin strongly sclerotized forming long groove with pointed apophysis on top (

Fig. 
3

). Cymbium with wide basolateral fold and proximal process overlapping dorsal margin of tibia (

Fig. 
4

). Embolus very thin and filiform, not visible in ventral view, and without embolic apophysis; median apophysis weak, spiniform; distal tegular apophysis large, with spatulate process on top (

Fig. 
2

).

Female genitalia (

Figs 
8–10

): Copulatory openings situated at middle of epigynum; epigynal plate developed, and forming a scape slender and very long (
Figs 6, 8
); entrance orifices clearly separated; intromittent ducts tubular and short; spermathecae ovate, wellsclerotized (

Figs 
9–10

).

Coloration and markings (
Figs 1, 5
). Female and male: carapace light brown, with pair of foliate markings; chelicerae yellowish brown; gnathocoxae, labium and sternum light yellowish brown; proximal part of all femora yellowish white, remainder of femora and other leg segments yellowish brown; opisthosoma dorsally blackish brown with white spots and bars, ventrally light beige, spinnerets yellow.
